Exports of Automotive Parts - Data Description

  • APEC: Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation
  • ASEAN: Association of Southeast Asian Nations
  • CAFTA: The Dominican Republic - Central America - US Free Trade Agreement
  • EU without UK: European Union without UK
  • EU: European Union
  • FTA: Free Trade Agreements
  • GCC: Gulf Cooperation Council
  • MERCOSUR: Latin American Southern Common Market
  • USMCA: United States - Mexico - Canada Agreement
  • WORLD: World Countries

Imports of Automotive Parts - Data Description

  • Imports by Country

US Consumer Confidence

  • US_Unemployment: Unemployment rate represents the number of unemployed as a percentage of the labor force.
  • US_Consumer_Confidence: Reflects consumer attitudes, buying intentions, vaction plans, and consumer expectations for inflation, stock prices, and interest rates.
  • US_Min_Hour_Wage: US Minimum Wage per Hour

Domestic Production & Sales

  • Total_Production: Annual U.S. Motor Vehicle Production (Thousands of Units)
  • Production_Passenger_Cars: A passenger car is a road motor vehicle, other than a motor cycle, intended for the carriage of passengers and designed to seat no more than nine persons (including the driver)
  • Production_Commercial_Vehicles: Includes trucks under 10,000 pounds including compact and conventional pickups, sport utility vehicles, minivans and vans.
  • Domestic_Sales: Includes U.S. sales of cars produced in U.S., Canada, and Mexico.
  • Sales_Passenger_Cars: Includes U.S. sales of cars produced in U.S., Canada, and Mexico.
  • Sales_Commercial_Vehicles: Includes U.S. sales of cars produced in U.S., Canada, and Mexico. Also, it includes trucks under 10,000 pounds including compact and conventional pickups, sport utility vehicles, minivans and vans.

Exploratory Data Analysis

Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) is about visualizing, transforming, and modelling your data. This report analyzes the U.S. automotive industry with the aim to explore patterns, trends, and factors that might explain its performance over a period of time. Briefly,EDA is a combination of data analysis tools including: a. statistical methods such as summary of descriptive statistics b. data visualization c. data analysis to address exploratory questions

Data Visualization Plots

Bar Plots

Create data.frame() to visualize exports and imports data

exports<-data.frame(exports_data$Year,exports_data$WORLD,exports_data$USMCA,exports_data$APEC,exports_data$EU28)
colnames(exports)<-c('Year','World','USMCA','APEC','EU')

imports<-data.frame(imports_data$Year,imports_data$WORLD,imports_data$Mexico,imports_data$Canada)
colnames(imports)<-c('Year','World','Mexico','Canada')
# USMCA Exports by Year
ggplot(exports, aes(x=Year, y=USMCA)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", fill="skyblue") + scale_fill_grey() + # Add bars to the plot
    labs(title = "Exports of Automotive Parts", # Add a title
       subtitle = "Exports to USMCA", # Add a subtitle
       caption = "The International Trade Administration - U.S. Department of Commerce", # Add a caption
       x = "Year")

# US Imports by Year
ggplot(imports, aes(x=Year, y=Mexico)) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity", fill="orange") + scale_fill_grey() + # Add bars to the plot
  labs(title = "U.S. Imports of Automotive Parts", # Add a title
       subtitle = "Imports from Mexico", # Add a subtitle
       caption = "The International Trade Administration - U.S. Department of Commerce", # Add a caption
       x = "Year")

Domestic Sales & Sales Passenger Cars

Extract data

domestic_sales<-domestic_production_sales %>% select(Year, Domestic_Sales:Sales_Commercial_Vehicles) %>% filter(Year>1993) 
ggplot(domestic_sales,aes(x=Year,y=Domestic_Sales,fill=Sales_Passenger_Cars))+
  geom_bar(stat="identity")+
  theme_minimal()+
  labs(title="U.S. Sales of Commercial Vehicles 1994-2020")

ggplot(domestic_sales,aes(x=Year,y=Domestic_Sales,fill=Sales_Commercial_Vehicles))+
  geom_bar(stat="identity")+
  theme_minimal()+
  labs(title="U.S. Sales of Passenger Vehicles 1994-2020")

Boxplots

  • Boxplots display how your data’s values are spread out. Boxplots are standardized way of displaying the distribution of data based on a five number summary:
  1. minimum
  2. first quartile [Q1]
  3. median
  4. third quartile [Q3]
  5. maximum

create a new dataset to display boxplots of exports by region

exports_boxplots=subset(exports,select=-c(Year,World))
boxplot(exports_boxplots,data=data,main="Dispersion of U.S. Exports of Auto Parts by Region over 2008-2021", 
        xlab="Region",ylab="Exports in USD Dollars",col=rainbow(ncol(trees)))

# create a new dataset to display boxplots of imports by country
imports_boxplots=subset(imports,select=-c(Year,World))
boxplot(imports_boxplots,data=data,main="Dispersion of U.S. Imports of Auto Parts by Region over 2008-2021", 
        xlab="Region",ylab="Imports in USD Dollars",col=rainbow(ncol(trees)))

Line Plots

Domestic Sales by Year (Time Series Data)

plot(domestic_production_sales$Year,domestic_production_sales$Domestic_Sales, type="l",col="blue", lwd=1.5, xlab ="Year",ylab ="Thousands of Units", main = "Annual U.S. Motor Vehicle Sales")
lines(domestic_production_sales$Year,domestic_production_sales$Total_Production,col="red",lty=3)
legend("topleft", legend=c("Domestic Sales", "Total Production"),
       col=c("blue", "red"), lty = 1:2, cex=0.8)

introducing time series libraries

library(tseries)
## Registered S3 method overwritten by 'quantmod':
##   method            from
##   as.zoo.data.frame zoo
library(dygraphs)
domestic_production_ts<-ts(domestic_production_sales$Domestic_Sales,domestic_production_sales$Year,start=1965,end=2020,frequency=1) 
dygraph(domestic_production_ts, main="Annual U.S. Motor Vehicle Sales", ylab="Thousands of Units") %>% 
  dyOptions(colors = RColorBrewer::brewer.pal(4, "Dark2")) %>%
  dyShading(from = "2000-12-1",to = "2020-12-1", color="#FFE6E6") %>%
  dyShading(from="1965-1-1", to="2006-05-31", color="#CCEBD6") %>%
  dyEvent("2007-1-1","U.S. Subprime Mortage Crisis",labelLoc="bottom")

Linear Regression Analysis - PREDICTION

A * linear regression analysis consists in estimating a linear relationship between one dependent variable and one or more explanatory independent variables. For example, what are the factors that affect the weekly sales for a company?

Data manipulation

us_auto_sales<-domestic_production_sales %>% select(Year,Domestic_Sales:Sales_Commercial_Vehicles) %>% filter(Year>2006)
us_auto_sales<-right_join(us_auto_sales, us_consumer_confidence, by='Year') # join 2 databases by using year as a reference. 
us_auto_sales<-us_auto_sales[!(us_auto_sales$Year=="2021"),] # remove year 2021

correlation plot

corrplot(cor(us_auto_sales),type='upper',order='hclust',addCoef.col='black')

scatter plot

ggplot(us_auto_sales, aes(x=US_Consumer_Confidence, y=Sales_Passenger_Cars)) + 
  geom_point(shape=19, size=3) + # Add points of the scatterplot
  labs(title = "Relationship between US Consumer Confidence & Car Sales", # Add title
       caption = "Bureau of Transportation Statistics", # Add data source
       x="US Consumer Confidence", y="Car Sales (Thousands of Units)") +  # Rename axes titles
  theme_classic() # Use a predefined theme of the graph

ggplot(us_auto_sales, aes(x=US_Unemployment, y=Domestic_Sales)) + 
  geom_point(shape=19, size=3) + # Add points of the scatterplot
  labs(title = "Relationship between US Unemployment & Domestic Car Sales", # Add title
       caption = "Bureau of Transportation Statistics", # Add data source
       x="US Unemployment", y="Car Sales (Thousands of Units)") +  # Rename axes titles
  theme_classic() # Use a predefined theme of the graph

estimation of linear regression model

Time Series Data - FORECASTING

  • Time series analysis is a specific way of analyzing a sequence of data points collected over a period of time. Generally, time series analysis requires a large number of data points to ensure consistency and reliability (Tableau Software).

loading time series libraries

Main Insights

  1. Descriptive Data Analysis

    • On average, U.S. exports of automotive parts to the USMCA region approximately represented USD$ 5,320,000,000 over the period 2008-2021 whereas the APEC represented USD$ 6,144,000,000.

    • According to the boxplots, the APEC region shows greater exports variability than the USMCA and EU regions.

  2. Results

    • There is a positive linear relationship between U.S. Automotive Domestic Sales and Consumer Confidence. We would expect that an increase in the consumer confidence in 1 unit might represent an increase of approximately 92.50 units in the dependent variable, holding eveything else constant.

    • There is a negative linear relationship between U.S. Automotive Domestic Sales and Consumer Confidence, however, it is not statistically significant.
